I'm referring to this proposal: https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/Documentation/design-docs/AssemblyLoadContext.ContextualReflection.md

The propose mechanism suggests that if an assembly cannot be loaded from the ALC set as the "current" context, then it would fallback to AssemblyLoadContext.Default.

May I suggest that it falls back to the predecessor ALC to enable patterns such as this:

```
var alc1 = AssemblyLoadContext.Default
var alc2 = new AssemblyLoadContext();
var alc3 = new AssemblyLoadContext();

Using (var globalScope = alc1.EnterScope())
{
  Using (var commonScope = alc2.EnterScope())
  {
    Using (var vendorScope = alc3.EnterScope())
  {
  
   }
  }
}
```
In this situation, if assemblies cannot be resolved from the current scope they fallback for resolution from predecessor scope making it possible to define a hierarchy.

